    <main>
        <div class="hero-section">
            <h2>The Ancient Religion of Light and Truth</h2>
            <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; max-width: 800px; margin: 1rem auto;">
                Explore one of humanity's oldest monotheistic faiths, founded by the prophet Zarathustra (Zoroaster).
                Zoroastrianism centers on the eternal cosmic struggle between Ahura Mazda (Wise Lord) and Angra Mainyu
                (Destructive Spirit), emphasizing the sacred fire, ethical dualism, and the path of good thoughts,
                good words, and good deeds.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="respect-notice">
            <h3 style="color: var(--mythos-primary); margin-top: 0;">üôè Living Tradition</h3>
            <p>
                <strong>Important:</strong> Zoroastrianism is a living religion with active practitioners worldwide,
                particularly in Iran and India (Parsis). This content is presented with deep respect for the faith
                and its adherents. Descriptions are based on historical texts (Avesta, Gathas) and scholarly sources,
                not as definitive religious doctrine.
            </p>
        </div>

        <section>
            <h2 style="color: var(--mythos-primary);">üî• Core Concepts</h2>

            <div class="subsection-card">
                <h3>‚öñÔ∏è <a href="cosmology/index.html">Cosmic Dualism</a></h3>
                <p>The fundamental struggle between Asha (Truth/Order) and Druj (Lie/Chaos), personified by Ahura Mazda
                   and Angra Mainyu. Unlike absolute dualism, Zoroastrianism teaches that good will ultimately triumph,
                   and Angra Mainyu will be defeated at the end of time.</p>
                <div class="sub-links">
                    <a href="cosmology/creation.html" class="sub-link">Creation Myth</a>
                    <a href="cosmology/afterlife.html" class="sub-link">Afterlife Journey</a>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="subsection-card">
                <h3>üî• Sacred Fire</h3>
                <p>Fire (Atar) is the supreme symbol of Ahura Mazda's divine light and wisdom. Fire temples house the
                   eternal flame, which must never be extinguished. Fire represents purity, truth, and the presence of
                   the divine in the physical world.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="subsection-card">
                <h3>üí≠ Ethical Path: Good Thoughts, Good Words, Good Deeds</h3>
                <p>The threefold ethical foundation of Zoroastrianism (Humata, Hukhta, Huvarshta). Every individual has
                   free will to choose between good and evil, and their choices directly impact the cosmic struggle
                   between Asha and Druj.</p>
        </section>

        <section style="margin-top: 3rem;">
            <h2 style="color: var(--mythos-primary);">üë§ Deities & Divine Beings</h2>

            <div class="subsection-card">
                <h3>‚ö° <a href="deities/index.html">The Divine Forces</a></h3>
                <p>While Ahura Mazda is the supreme creator deity, Zoroastrianism includes many divine beings who
                   assist in maintaining cosmic order and battling evil.</p>
                <div class="sub-links">
                    <a href="deities/ahura-mazda.html" class="sub-link">Ahura Mazda (Wise Lord)</a>
                    <a href="deities/mithra.html" class="sub-link">Mithra (Covenant & Light)</a>
                    <a href="deities/anahita.html" class="sub-link">Anahita (Waters & Fertility)</a>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="subsection-card">
                <h3>‚ú® The Amesha Spentas</h3>
                <p>The "Bounteous Immortals" - seven divine emanations of Ahura Mazda, each representing a virtue and
                   protecting an aspect of creation (fire, metals, earth, water, plants, cattle, humanity).</p>
            </div>

            <div class="subsection-card">
                <h3>üòà Angra Mainyu & the Daevas</h3>
                <p>The Destructive Spirit and his evil minions who oppose Ahura Mazda. The daevas are not fallen angels
                   but rather malevolent spirits who have always existed in opposition to truth and order.</p>
        </section>

